Submitted 2009-06-24 22:08:57 A robotic arm is a type of robot that can be manipulated to function in similar ways that a human arm does.
Robotic Arm Favorites There are several types of robotic arms but the most widely used are the SCARA and Cartesian robots.
Cartesian robotic arms are also called gantry or rectilinear robots and they are popular with manufacturing companies because they are able to move in many linear directions.
Cartesian robot arms are effective in tasks that require pick and place, assembly work and welding among others.
Cartesian robots are also highly effective in sealing work such as the placement of adhesives.

Other applications that Cartesian robotic arms are suitable for include: - Repetitive tasks that involve a lot of data handling as in research and development - Handling and loading of machines - Cellphone and circuit board production - Palletizing functions While Cartesian robots operate with high precision, there are drawbacks associated with this type of robotic arm.
Space size is a major issue with Cartesian robots as these equipment demand spaces much larger than those occupied by SCARA robots.
Most notable is the fact that SCARA robots are speedy and sturdy equipment.
The parts of a SCARA robot lend themselves easily to protective sealing which is why SCARAs can function even under water.
Other applications for SCARA robotic arms are: - Stacking and de-stacking - Dispensing - Welding There are also space issues associated with the SCARA robot.
Also, SCARA robots are difficult to operate.

TESTING POKER AI Playing a quick single table game of Texas Holdem takes around 30 minutes on average with human players.
Ideally you would perform your testing by having human players play against the AI and trying to find problems with it.
I've found it takes at least ten games to begin to get a clear picture of the qualities of an AI player, and more like a hundred games to be really sure.
This often creates an unreasonably burden on the testing department, and introduces a very long delay in getting feedback on AI changes.
The AI should be set up so that different variants of AI can play against each other in a very high speed set of games.
You should also code a few simplistic poker AI's into the mix, such as an AI that always goes all in, or another that simply always raises with a hand better than a pair of fives.
Then you set your AI loose against these opponents, and make sure that it wins the appropriate percentage of games.
The best use of your human testers is to try to get them to find an exploit of the AI, then you can codify this exploit into a temporary AI opponent to include in your test suite.

And a Greek study published in the March 2007 issue of The International Journal of Animal Biosciences concluded that even under less-than-average management conditions, AI is more profitable than the best natural-service scenario.

The study used a partial budget to compare a highly managed natural-service program that featured the use of breeding-soundness exams, strict vaccination protocols and a rotational-breeding system with an AI program that featured a modified Presynch-Ovsynch protocol.
Even when you shift these numbers, AI comes out on top economically 66 percent of the time.
Reproductive efficiency But even if they are a little more expensive, bulls are still more efficient at finding cows in heat and getting them bred than any AI program, you say.
In a 2002 California study, researchers did find that in herds with poor estrus detection, use of natural-service sires did result in a higher pregnancy rate than an AI program.
However, herds using a combination of AI and bulls or mostly bulls had longer dry periods.

Research at the University of California, also published in the August 2005 issue of Theriogenology, shows that cows in AI pens have a higher risk of pregnancy across all days in milk than cows in bull pens.
It concluded that you may be better off to leave cows in the AI pen for at least an extra breeding or two before moving them to the bull pen.
Furthermore, researchers have been able to show that timed AI can out-perform bulls when it comes to breeding sub-fertile cows.

A 2006 field observation by University of Florida reproductive specialist Bill Thatcher and Risco examined the ability of timed AI, as well as re-synchronization to timed AI, to get cows pregnant in a 2,000-cow herd that used bulls extensively.
Cows considered infertile or not pregnant after ample exposure to bulls were enrolled in a timed-AI protocol.
In addition, timed AI allows for immediate submission of all cows at the designated waiting period.
